  aArms races among invertebrates, intelligence gathering by the immune system and alarm calls by marmots are but a few of nature's security strategies that have been tested and modified over billions of years. This provocative book applies lessons from nature to our own toughest security problems—from global terrorism to the rise of infectious disease to natural disasters. Written by a truly multidisciplinary group including paleobiologists, anthropologists, psychologists, ecologists, and national security experts, it considers how models and ideas from evolutionary biology can improve national security strategies ranging from risk assessment, security analysis, and public policy to long-term strategic goals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAdaptation (Biology). 0aNatural selection. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  adarwinian.  aecology.  aevolution and adaptation.  aevolutionary adaptation.  aevolutionary biology.  aglobal terrorism.  aimmune system.  ainfectious disease.  ainvertebrate.  amultidisciplinary group.  anational security.  anatural disaster.  apaleobiologist.  apsychologist.  arisk assessment.  asecurity analysis.  atheory of evolution.1 aAlcorta, Candace S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtran, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlumstein, Daniel T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDietl, Gregory P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Dominic D. P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJordán, Ferenc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLafferty, Kevin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/